The third program then reads from the same stdin? but the second program has already consumed the first token and then the rest of the tokens remain? Actually, no: the second program runs to completion and then the third program starts. The second program does not read beyond the first token? because after reading the first token it processes it and then doesn't read more? Actually, the second program does:

        String number = sc.next();

        and then it processes that string and then ends.

The first element of the array is stored in aa[0] (Java) which in Fortran we would store in aa(1) if we use 1-indexing? but we can use 0-indexing if we want. We will use 1-indexing for Fortran? or 0-indexing? Since Fortran can use arrays with any index, we will use 0-indexing to match Java. Alternatively, we can use 1-indexing and adjust the indices. Let me translate the first program carefully. The first program:

        int [] aa = new int[n];
        ... then it fills aa by inserting at position j the value 'a' (which goes from n-1 down to 0) ... Then it prints: for i from 0 to n-1: (aa[i] + 1) and a space. So the first element printed is aa[0]+1.
